In The Master Algorithm, Pedro Domingos (2017:51) refers to &quot;the rival schools of thought that exist within machine learning.&quot; The main ones, according to Domingos (ibid.:52-53), are as follows:

*symbolists*, for whom &quot;all intelligence can be reduced to manipulating *symbols*, in the same way that a mathematician solves equations by replacing expressions by other expressions.&quot;

*connectionists*, who seek to reverse engineer the brain and often use an algorithm that &quot;compares a system&#039;s output with the desired one and then successively changes the *connections* in layer after layer of [artificial] neurons so as to bring the output closer to what it should be.&quot;

*evolutionaries*, who believe that learning can be modeled on *natural selection*.

*Bayesians*, who rely on probabilistic inference and *Bayes&#039;* theorem.

*analogizers*, who recognize similarities between situations and then infer other further *similarities* between those situations.
